        <h1>Historical Figures</h1>
        <div id="N_R_B">
            <h2>Ned Ludd</h2>
                <p>Ludd started the Luddite movement, which began as a protest against machines replacing facotry workers in factories.  Luddites are not necessarily against technology and the technological progress.  Rather, they advocate integrating technology in such a way that will attenuate the damage done to the working class.</p>
            <h2>Teddy Roosevelt</h2>
                <img src="Rough_rider.jpg" alt="into the wind">
                <p>He was a Rough Rider and the 26th president of the United States.</p>
            <h2>Richary Byrd</h2>
                <P>Richard Byrd was an explorer and scientist, whose work is captured in his book <a href="https://www.amazon.com/Alone-Classic-Adventure-Richard-Byrd/dp/1559634634">'Alone.'</a></P>
        </div>
        <div id="P_G">
            <h2>Ezra Pound</h2>
                <p>Do you know where the phrase "pound for pound" comes from?  I don't. And it's not becuase of Ezra Pound.  He's a poet who was born in Haily, Idaho.</p>
                <p>Pound's famous works include:</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>The Cantos</li>
                        <li>Make it New</li>
                        <li>ABC of Reading</li>
                        <li>the Spirit of Romance</li>
                    </ul>
            <h2>Marcus Garvey</h2>
                <p>One of Garvey's provocative ideas was the Black Star Line, a cruise line that's purpose was the bring African Americans back to Africa, circa 1920.</p>
        </div>
